content.text:
I have analyzed the issue where the closing parenthesis `)` of a parenthesized expression was unexpectedly indented when used within a block (like an `if` block) in `ktlint_official` code style. This was due to the `IndentationRule` using default indentation for the last child of a `PARENTHESIZED` element, which added an extra level of indentation to the closing parenthesis.

I have implemented a fix in `IndentationRule.kt` specifically for the `ktlint_official` code style. The fix ensures that both the opening `(` and closing `)` of a `PARENTHESIZED` expression align with the expression's own indentation level, while the content inside remains indented. This behavior matches how other similar elements like `VALUE_ARGUMENT_LIST` and `CLASS_BODY` are handled. I have also removed the restriction that prevented `PARENTHESIZED` from starting an indent context when used as a direct or near-direct child of an `if` statement, as it was causing inconsistent indentation of the expression's content.

For other code styles, I preserved the existing behavior to maintain compatibility with the Kotlin IDE plugin formatter, as requested in the issue discussion.

**Changes:**
- Modified `IndentationRule.kt` to handle `PARENTHESIZED` elements by starting an indent context with `firstChildIndent = ""` and `lastChildIndent = ""` when `codeStyle == ktlint_official`.
- Created `IndentationIssueTest.kt` with test cases reproducing the reported issue and verifying the fix.

All new tests passed, and existing `IndentationRuleTest` tests also passed, ensuring no regressions.

```kotlin
// ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/IndentationRule.kt

            node.elementType == PARENTHESIZED -> {
                if (codeStyle == ktlint_official) {
                    startIndentContext(
                        fromAstNode = node,
                        firstChildIndent = "",
                        lastChildIndent = "",
                    )
                } else if (node.treeParent.treeParent.elementType != IF) {
                    startIndentContext(node)
                }
            }
```

